<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>What is the primary difference between the income and expenditure approaches to calculating GDP?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Income approach counts only wages, while expenditure counts all spending</option>
            <option letter="b">Income approach measures earnings, while expenditure measures spending</option>
            <option letter="c">Income approach includes foreign transactions, while expenditure doesn't</option>
            <option letter="d">Income approach uses base year prices, while expenditure uses current prices</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The income approach measures GDP by summing all earnings (wages, rent, interest, profit), while the expenditure approach measures GDP by summing all spending (C + I + G + NX). Both should yield the same total.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>How does a decrease in the value of the dollar affect net exports?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Decreases exports and increases imports</option>
            <option letter="b">Increases exports and decreases imports</option>
            <option letter="c">Increases both exports and imports</option>
            <option letter="d">Decreases both exports and imports</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>A weaker dollar makes U.S. goods cheaper for foreigners (increasing exports) and foreign goods more expensive for Americans (decreasing imports), thereby improving net exports.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>What causes the "sticky" prices and wages in the short-run aggregate supply curve?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Government price controls</option>
            <option letter="b">Labor union contracts and menu costs</option>
            <option letter="c">International trade agreements</option>
            <option letter="d">Central bank policies</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Prices and wages are sticky in the short run due to factors like labor union contracts, menu costs (expense of changing prices), and long-term wage agreements that prevent immediate adjustment.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>If the nominal interest rate is 8% and the inflation rate is 3%, what is the real interest rate?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">11%</option>
            <option letter="b">5%</option>
            <option letter="c">2.67%</option>
            <option letter="d">24%</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The real interest rate is calculated by subtracting the inflation rate from the nominal interest rate: 8% - 3% = 5%. This represents the actual return after accounting for inflation.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
